5.
    a?
        The wooden ring makes the apparatus safer for the student to use as wood is an insulator, so if the student needs to adjust the apparatus he will not get burned. In addition, the wooden ring also acts to counterbalance the tacks so that the apparatus will not fall over or otherwise unexpectedly and autonomously disassemble, which has the potential of scattering hot metal and burning the student.
    b.
        The end of the metal strips over the flame becomes hot as it is heated. This means that the mean kinetic energy of the metal atoms in that area increases. These atoms collide with neighbouring atoms, transferring this energy to them. The metal strips heat up beginning from the end at the flame, which is the hottest; the heat travells towards the end furthest from the flame, which is the coldest. As the end furthest from the flame heats up, those metal atoms bump into the wax molecules, transferring their energy into the wax, and ultimately melting it.
    c.
        i.
            A bar chart is used as the dependent variable is numeric and continuous, but the independent variable is categorical (and hence discontinuous).
        ii?
            The student could improve the reliability of their results by repeating the experiment three times, or by using a pressure-sensor to automatically stop the timer when a tack falls.
        iii.
            I do not agree with the student's conclusion. This is because it takes energy to melt wax, so the material that transmits energy the best will melt the wax the quickest. Iron, however, melted the wax the slowest, as evidenced by the fact that it took the pin longest to drop on iron.
