    b.
        i.
            The pressure of trapped gas increases as its temperature increases because as the temperature increases, the mean kinetic energy of the particles of the gas increase. These particles are moving randomly, so will collide with the walls of the barometer; when they collide, they exert a force. When the mean kinetic energy of the particles of gas increases, so does this force; since pressure is force/area (area = area of walls the barometer), the pressure increases as area is constant.
        ii.
            12/23*38 = 19.8260869565 ~= 19.8 kPa
12.
    a.
        Chemical energy -> kinetic energy (food to fingers moving);
        Kinetic energy -> potential energy (fingers moving the marble -> lifts the marble)
        kinetic energy -> sound energy (placing the marble at point A)
        potential energy -> kinetic energy (marble rolls down the pipes marble run)
        kinetic energy -> sound energy (marble drops down the vertical chutes/marble rolls down the marble run)
    b.
        i.
            The student could mark out a short distance in a flat straight line from point B. The student could then, using a stopwatch, start the time when the marble crosses point B, and then stop the time when the marble crosses that marker. The student could then measure the distance, and calculate the speed by using the formula speed = distance/time, since both time and distance are known.
        ii.
            exit KE = 1/2 * 5.5/1000 * 0.76^2 = 0.0015884 J
            Starting GPE = 0.21 * 5.5/1000 * 9.8 = 0.011319J
            so energy lost = 0.011319 - 0.0015884 = 0.0097306 ~= 0.00973 J
        
        
        